\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 
Would you have any ideas what these people might be when you were young? From what we were discussing you were saying that there were sort of areas of different type of people in different districts. Can you enlarge on that a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 
Mr F. Do you want that on tape? Well - no, but all I can say is if you'd got - a fairly large scale map of - of the 
- district, Nottingham districts - shall we say Sneinton or just round it, the immediate - neighbourhood of Sneinton - you could actually mark off - these - areas where these different classes of people lived. And you go from - the lowest of the lot which
 
were tramps, vagrants, lodging house keepers and so on, in the lower social scale, absolutely the lowest. That was Narrow Marsh. With the - lodging houses, doss houses as we used to call them and they used to charge about fourpence - a night, four old pen
c
e of course, a night for them to sleep - in these places, and they weren't - too clean, they were dingy holes you see, and it was mostly in that Narrow Marsh district. And then you - close by, not very far away - you've got one step higher, which was call
e
d the Bottoms. Now these were - mostly occupied by the poorer paid - people. You see, I mean - when you had to go to work for perhaps about as low as ten shillings a week or so on, occasional jobs and all that kind of thing, well - what shall we call them
,
 not skilled workers, not even semi-skilled, just ordinary labourers and things like that, well their wages weren't very high, so - they lived in these places in this district, that was the Bottoms as it was called. Well this was mostly comprised of - str
e
ets of poorer quality houses, all ribbon built houses, with very poor conditions, and these yards, which I've described to you you know. And then - from that you come - with the St Annes district which was - just the least shade better, slum area. And the
n
 you come up - the - just the - round again by up where the Sneinton Road was, that was - just what shall we call - lower middle class, put it that way. It wasn't actually slum - but it was - a shade higher than the - these what I've spoken about. And the
n
 the other side of the church - you get what could be called, or would be called today - Newer Sneinton, and they were better class houses altogether with water - water - laid into the houses and so on. But still - they still had outside toilets. You see.
 
But - they were a better - better class houses. And when you ask whether you could move from one district to another, this was the - mostly - on the system that if you got a better wage - you moved out of these - bad areas shall we say, into the better cl
ass areas because you could afford to pay the rents. Everything was on what you could afford it or not those days, that was all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 And the houses were to be had you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Oh yes, you could get - easy get houses, you could leave - on a week's notic
e, you gave a week's notice to the landlord, or the agent, and then you - you could - move. The houses even were advertised in the papers, as to let. You see. And all you did was to go to the agent or write, can I have the key, you had a look round the ho
u
se, you either accepted it or you didn't, if you did well then you went in and that was it. But if you'd got the money - you can afford to go in a better district. Of course there's always this attached to it, the same as there is today. Now - you - if yo
u
've lived in an area so long - and you wasn't - too badly off - I mean even in these middle class - houses - you form your own - friends, and so on, and it was like tearing a tree up by its roots to move out, although you could afford to. It didn't always
 follow, but - the - the money - and when you could afford it was one of the main items.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 You said you didn't like Sneinton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 
No, not when we first went there because - we lived on - Maple Street, up Hyson Green, you know where the forest is, well 
they was nice houses, bay windows and - when we went to Sneinton you saw all the people sitting out on the front doorsteps Sundays and - well we - we'd never - we never saw that you know, 'til we went down there and that, and my sister next to me says to 
mother what made you come down to this hole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 And what was the answer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 
Well, we were going to be at the shop you see, 'cos we - the sister that - older than her had made the manageress to look after the shop. Well there was all the house part vaca
nt. So mother thought, well we'll keep eye on her, 'cos this was the one that used to go out, stay out late at night. And - we went to live over the premises you see. But - we didn't care much for the district when we first went to be truthful, I didn't s
o - we had to get used to it and that was that. And I was there 'til I was twenty-four and then I went back to Radford you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 
Still on your first school, if you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 You'd get the strap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 At the first school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Mm, get the cane, yes, you would
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Would you have got the strap at the first school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Yes, if you did anything wrong, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 For what sort of things would you have got that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Well if you didn't - pay attention to what they was telling you and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 And the girls would have got the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3434615 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14642234 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3279529\charrsid12135944 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
